╔═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════╗
║  SHIP'S ARCHIVE: cd & pwd                                     ║
║  Classification: Core Tool                                    ║
╚═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════╝

┌─ ORIGIN STORY ─────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│                                                                │
│  Both commands date to early Unix (1971). "cd" stands for     │
│  "change directory" and "pwd" for "print working directory."  │
│  The concept of a "current directory" was revolutionary -     │
│  before Unix, you had to specify full paths for everything.   │
│  The working directory is stored in an environment variable   │
│  called $PWD, which the shell updates as you navigate.        │
│                                                                │
└────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘

┌─ MENTAL MODEL ─────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│                                                                │
│  Think of the filesystem as a tree, and "you" as standing     │
│  on one branch at any given moment:                           │
│                                                                │
│              / (root)                                          │
│             /|\                                                │
│            / | \                                               │
│         home usr var                                           │
│          |                                                     │
│        kenny     ← cd /home/kenny brings you here             │
│         /|\                                                    │
│        / | \                                                   │
│     docs  projects  .bashrc                                    │
│             |                                                  │
│           shell-odyssey  ← pwd shows: /home/kenny/projects/... │
│                                                                │
│  Special shortcuts:                                            │
│    cd ~     → go to your home directory ($HOME)               │
│    cd ..    → go up one level (parent directory)              │
│    cd -     → go back to previous directory (toggle)          │
│    cd       → same as cd ~ (go home)                          │
│                                                                │
└────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘

┌─ CONNECTIONS ──────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│                                                                │
│  • Works well with: ls, find, pushd/popd                      │
│  • Alternatives: pushd/popd (for directory stacks)            │
│  • Builds toward: Understanding paths, $HOME, shell variables │
│                                                                │
└────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘

┌─ ARIA'S INSIGHT ───────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│                                                                │
│  "The 'cd -' trick is underrated. It toggles between your     │
│  current directory and the previous one - perfect when you're │
│  jumping between two locations repeatedly. And remember:      │
│  if you ever feel lost, 'pwd' tells you exactly where you     │
│  are. Getting lost is part of learning the ship's layout."    │
│                                                                │
└────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
